Evangelical Churches in the Netherlands -- t17 Religious Exclusivism, Social Inclusion: Missiological Reflections -- t18 Religious Exclusivism, Social Inclusion: Theological Reflections -- tIndex -- tIndex of Manuscripts0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aIs it possible to be religiously exclusive and socially inclusive? How do we deal with those outside of our own religious community who have completely different and sometimes conflicting views on what should be considered true and right behaviour? What if a religious tradition orders the expulsion or killing of those who leave the faith community and adopt another worldview? This book focuses on biblical texts concerning exclusivity and apostasy, studying different interpretations of such texts. It starts with the Jewish and Christian tradition of the Hebrew Bible, continues with texts from the New Testament, and explores diverse social studies to find ways of understanding the relationship between exclusion and inclusion today. Part of this exploration is the interaction with Jewish and Islamic voices. The collection ends with a systematic and missiological reflection on the issues Christian churches and other religious communities must address today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aApostasy. 0aReligion and sociology. 0aReligious communities. 0aTheology. 4aContemporary History. 4aContemporary Society. 4aCultural Studies. 4aReligion and Philosophy. 4aReligion and Theology. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh  aExclusion, inclusion, apostasy, Christianity, Judaism, Islam.1 aBakker, Henk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarentsen, 